So far, pretty standard.  However, this knight development is a little off the modern beaten track.  I knew a correspondence player in this country who used to play this with the express purpose of continuing to d5 and exchanging on e7.  Otherwise I don't really know what theory lies behind this move.

Now: ask yourself this question.  Is it safe for White to recapture on d4?  Has he a better option?
[?] This recapture might look safe, but in fact is quite unplayable, as the sequel will show.  Better would have been 9.Nd5.
No real choice, but...
No real choice, but...
Now White is in the toils of a Noah's Ark Trap.  I happen to know that Joe is aware of the notion of the N.A.T. so I'm a little surprised to see him walk into this one!
Trapping the bishop.  This 'trap' is a well known feature of the Ruy Lopez.

[!] I give it this mark of approbation, as showing a determination to make the best of the disastrous situation facing White so early in the game.
[!?] This move is not without risks, ...Ne8 being safer.

[?] Rather better was 13.Qe4 or maybe 13.Qf3, attacking knight and rook both.  Black would have had to find 13...d5! to avoid the loss of either. E.g.: 14.Qe4 d5!  15.exd6 e.p. Qxd6 (threatening mate on h2) 16.Bf4 Qd7.  This would have led to a complicated tactical melee, favouring Black, for sure, but in the circumstances very welcome to White.
Less effective than it would have been a move ago, as the knight now has protection.
Less effective than it would have been a move ago, as the knight now has protection.
[?] Oversight ... or a sacrifice for attack?

[!]  Best.  If Black has anything for the slight material sacrifices, the onus is on him to show it!  In fact, objectively speaking White has the edge right now.  All the same the situation is complicated and combative - and the slugfest is just beginning!
Natural and good.  But 16.cxb3 was also worth considering.
Natural and good.  But 16.cxb3 was also worth considering.
Setting up an 'X-ray' attack against h2.  White had better beware!
[!] Fine response!

[?!]  Obviously what White had in mind from his previous move, but Black would have had more to worry about after 18.Qc6!!    The idea is, of course, 18...Qxc6 19.Nxe7ch Kh8  20.Nxc6.  If instead 18...Qd8, then 19.Qxc8! Qxc8 {19...Qxd5 20.Qxg4}   20.Nxe7ch Kh8  21.Nxc8 Rxc8 21,Rxa6 with a fine game for White.
